!/ Text_Annotation
$s#  !p1  9
$e: div @8
$t. 
|> 
<|| The application&rsquo;s histogram display is interactive, ||>
<|| so that users can manually select colors ||>
<|| assigned to thematic roles such as canonical ||>
<|| foreground and background. ||>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;&#9135;
<br>
<|| Algorithms that are fine-tuned interactively can then ||>
<|| be applied automatically across an image series. ||>  
<|| For example, center and periphery histograms ||>
<|| could be consulted to estimate foreground and ||> 
<|| background poles without user input. <| In general, ||>
<|| interactive histograms allow histogram data to be ||>
<|| leveraged for color-sensitive (as compared to ||>
<|| grayscale) Computer Vision algorithms. ||>
/.
$y: [$large-box]
$p# 1 4
